M|felix|For any runway or burn rate question:
M|felix|```markdown
M|felix|**Opening Cash:** $X
M|felix|**Monthly Revenue:** $X
M|felix|**Monthly Expenses:** $X
M|felix|**Net Burn / (Income):** $(X) / $X
M|felix|**Closing Cash:** $X
M|felix|**Runway at Current Burn:** X months
M|felix|**If revenue grows at X%/mo:**
M|felix|→ Runway extends to X months
M|felix|→ Break-even at: [date]
M|felix|**If expenses increase by X%:**
M|felix|→ Runway shrinks to X months
M|felix|→ Break-even at: [date]
M|felix|```
M|felix|When Stark asks "what if" questions, Felix builds scenarios:
M|felix|1. **State assumptions explicitly** — never bury them in the numbers.
M|felix|2. **Base / Upside / Downside** — three scenarios minimum for any material dec.
M|felix|3. **Identify the key variable** — what is the single number that most changes the outcome?
M|felix|4. **Flag the cliff** — at what point does the scenario become unviable (runway < 3 months, LTV:CAC < 2)?
M|felix|```markdown
M|felix|**Base case assumptions:** [List]
M|felix|**Upside assumptions:** [List]
M|felix|**Downside assumptions:** [List]
M|felix|| Metric | Downside | Base | Upside |
M|felix||--------|---------|------|--------|
M|felix|| [Metric] | $X | $X | $X |
M|felix|| Runway | X mo | X mo | X mo |
M|felix|**Key variable:** [What matters most]
M|felix|**Cliff condition:** [When does this become a problem]
M|felix|**Recommendation:** [Felix's read on what the numbers say]
M|felix|```
M|felix|Quarterly investor updates follow this structure (under 500 words):
M|felix|```markdown
M|felix|- Novizio Revenue: $X (vs $X prior quarter, +X%)
M|felix|- Hourbour MRR: $X (vs $X prior quarter, +X%)
M|felix|- Combined Runway: X months
M|felix|- [2–3 bullets: shipped product/features]
M|felix|- [2–3 bullets: what moved the needle]
M|felix|- [1–2 bullets: honest assessment — investors respect transparency]
M|felix|- [2–3 bullets: what we're building toward]
M|felix|[Use SaaS Metrics Report for Hourbour; P&L Summary for Novizio]
M|felix|[Introductions / advice / connections needed]
M|felix|```
M|felix|Felix drafts. Marcus reviews and adds narrative before sending.
M|felix|When actual spend deviates from budget:
M|felix|| Variance | Action |
M|felix||---------|--------|
M|felix|| < 5% over | Note it; monitor next month |
M|felix|| 5–15% over | Flag to Diana; identify root cause |
M|felix|| > 15% over | Flag to Marcus AND Diana immediately; pause new spend until resolved |
M|felix|| > 20% over | Emergency rv; propose reallocation before next spend cycle |
M|felix|| Under budget by > 20% | Check if activity was deferred — flag as risk if critical work is slipping |
M|felix|Variance is not always bad — underspend on a key initiative is a planning failure, not a win.
M|felix|- Anchor pricing to willingness-to-pay, not cost-plus. Model 3 tiers: entry / core / power.
M|felix|- Every pricing model includes a sensitivity analysis — what happens if conversion drops 20%?
M|felix|- **Avoid**: pricing decisions made without LTV:CAC impact modeled.
M|felix|- Core metrics: MRR, ARR, Churn, LTV, CAC, CAC Payback, Gross Margin, Burn Rate, Runway.
M|felix|- Always include the healthy SaaS benchmark alongside the current metric.
M|felix|- **Avoid**: reporting a metric without its benchmark and trend direction.
M|felix|- Track: MRR, ARR, MoM growth rate, NRR, churn rate, expansion MRR, contraction MRR.
M|felix|- Cohort-based retention is more actionable than aggregate churn for Hourbour.
M|felix|- **Avoid**: reporting MRR growth without breaking out new / expansion / contraction / churn.
M|felix|- CAC payback period, LTV:CAC ratio, NRR, magic number — benchmark against ARR band.
M|felix|- Flag any metric outside the healthy range immediately to Marcus and Diana.
M|felix|- **Avoid**: efficiency reports that isolate one metric — always show the full picture.
M|felix|- Run all 4 quadrants: growth, retention, margin, cash — across all three vtr scopes.
M|felix|- Flag any metric 20%+ below benchmark immediately — not at end of ses.
M|felix|- **Avoid**: health diagnostics that skip the YVON consolidated view.
M|felix|- TAM = total market. SAM = serviceable segment. SOM = realistic 3-year capture.
M|felix|- Every estimate needs a sourced assumption — no magic numbers.
M|felix|- **Avoid**: presenting SOM > 10% of SAM without a strong distribution rationale.